[36m│[0m [1mProtocol: Ssh[0m [36m│[0m
[36m╰─────────────────────────────────────────╯[0m

[96m▸ Stack:[0m [32mETH>IP>TCP>SSH[0m
[96m▸ Status:[0m [93mβ Beta[0m

[96m▸ Description:[0m
  [2mSSH server using russh where the LLM handles authentication and shell sessions[0m


[96m━━━ Event Types ━━━[0m

[2mThis protocol can emit the following network events:[0m

[35m▸ Event: [1mssh_auth[0m
  [90mSSH authentication request received (username and auth method provided)[0m

  [36mEvent Data:[0m
    [34m•[0m [1musername[0m ([33mstring[0m): Username attempting to authenticate
    [34m•[0m [1mauth_type[0m ([33mstring[0m): Authentication method (e.g., 'password', 'publickey')

  [36mAvailable Actions:[0m
    [32m•[0m [1mssh_auth_decision[0m: Decide whether to allow SSH authentication for this user. Consider the user instruction to determine if this user should be allowed. Common scenarios: allow all users, allow specific usernames, deny all.
      [2mParameters:[0m
        - [1mallowed[0m ([33mboolean[0m): true to allow authentication, false to deny
      [2mExample:[0m [90m{
  "type": "ssh_auth_decision",
  "allowed": true
}[0m

[35m▸ Event: [1mssh_banner[0m
  [90mSSH shell session opened (send welcome banner/greeting)[0m

  [36mAvailable Actions:[0m
    [32m•[0m [1mssh_send_banner[0m: Send a banner or greeting message when the SSH shell session opens. This is typically a welcome message, MOTD (message of the day), or system information. If no banner is needed, use show_message to indicate that instead.
      [2mParameters:[0m
        - [1mbanner[0m ([33mstring[0m): The banner text to display (may include newlines)
      [2mExample:[0m [90m{
  "type": "ssh_send_banner",
  "banner": "Welcome to NetGet SSH Server!\nType 'help' for available commands.\n"
}[0m

[35m▸ Event: [1mssh_shell_command[0m
  [90mSSH shell command received from client[0m

  [36mEvent Data:[0m
    [34m•[0m [1mcommand[0m ([33mstring[0m): The command entered by the user

  [36mAvailable Actions:[0m
    [32m•[0m [1mssh_shell_response[0m: Respond to the SSH shell command. Parse the command and generate appropriate output. Common commands: pwd, ls, cd, cat, echo, help, exit, logout. Use memory (set_memory/append_memory) to track state like current directory or session variables.
      [2mParameters:[0m
        - [1mresponse[0m ([33mstring[0m): The command output to send back to the user
      [2mExample:[0m [90m{
  "type": "ssh_shell_response",
  "response": "/home/user\n"
}[0m
    [32m•[0m [1mclose_this_connection[0m: Close the SSH connection. Use this when the user types 'exit', 'logout', or explicitly requests to close/disconnect. The connection will be terminated gracefully.
      [2mExample:[0m [90m{
  "type": "close_this_connection"
}[0m

[35m▸ Event: [1msftp_operation[0m
  [90mSFTP client requested a filesystem operation[0m

  [36mEvent Data:[0m
    [34m•[0m [1moperation[0m ([33mstring[0m): The SFTP operation type (opendir, readdir, open, read, close, lstat, fstat, realpath)
    [34m•[0m [1mparams[0m ([33mstring[0m): Operation-specific parameters (path, handle, offset, etc.)

  [90mNo specific actions available for this event.[0m


[96m━━━ User-Triggered Actions ━━━[0m

[2mThese actions can be triggered by user input (not tied to network events):[0m

[32m•[0m [1mclose_ssh_connection[0m: Close a specific SSH connection (async action)
  [36mParameters:[0m
    - [1mconnection_id[0m ([33mstring[0m): Connection ID to close
  [2mExample:[0m [90m{
  "type": "close_ssh_connection",
  "connection_id": "conn_12345"
}[0m

[32m•[0m [1mlist_ssh_connections[0m: List all active SSH connections
  [2mExample:[0m [90m{
  "type": "list_ssh_connections"
}[0m

